definition.value: Propan-1-ol with a hydrogen at each of the 3 carbon positions substituted with a carboxylate group.
A phosphatidylcholine that is a glycerol phosphatide (phosphoglyceride, glycerophospholipid) in which the hydroxy group of choline is esterified with the phosphate group of phosphatidic acid.
A cholestanoid consisting of cholestane having a double bond at the 5,6-position as well as a 3beta-hydroxy group.
An azane that consists of a single nitrogen atom covelently bonded to three hydrogen atoms.
A branched fatty acid comprising propanoic acid carrying a methyl branch at C-2.

A sulfur hydride consisting of a single sulfur atom bonded to two hydrogen atoms. A highly poisonous, flammable gas with a characteristic odour of rotten eggs, it is often produced by bacterial decomposition of organic matter in the absence of oxygen.
A mucopolysaccharide composed of repeating beta-D-glucopyranuronosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-N-acetylgalactosaminyl units.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the hydroxy group of retinol with the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid.
A sulfur oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of both OH groups of sulfuric acid.
An octadec-9-enoic acid in which the double bond at C-9 has Z (cis) stereochemistry.
A carbonyl group with two C-bound amine groups. The commercially available fertilizer has an analysis of 46-0-0 (N-P2O5-K2O).
A 2-aminopurine carrying a 6-oxo substituent.
An inorganic peroxide consisting of two hydroxy groups joined by a covalent oxygen-oxygen single bond.
A lipid containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or di-ester. The term encompasses phosphatidic acids and phosphoglycerides.
The 11-cis-isomer of retinyl palmitate.
A UDP-amino sugar having N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine as the amino sugar component.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid consisting of hexadecanoic acid carrying methyl substituents at positions 3, 7, 11 and 15.
The D-enantiomer of proline.
Any hexose-1-phosphate which has D configuration at position 5 and alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A ribonucleoside composed of a molecule of adenine attached to a ribofuranose moiety via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.

A mucopolysaccharide composed of N-acetylglucosamine and glucuronic acid subunits. It is found in the connective tissues of vertebrates. A principal constituent of the extracellular matrix (ECM), it mediates the growth and metastasis of tumour cells.
A derivative of glycerol in which one hydroxy group, commonly but not necessarily primary, is esterified with phosphoric acid and the other two are esterified with fatty acids.
A 3',5'-cyclic purine nucleotide in which the purine nucleobase is specified as guanidine.
A bile acid that is 5beta-cholan-24-oic acid bearing three alpha-hydroxy substituents at position 3, 7 and 12.
An optically active form of cysteine having D-configuration.
Compounds having the structure RSR (R =/= H). Such compounds were once called thioethers.

Any benzoquinone derived from 2,3-dimethoxy-5-methylbenzoquinone; one of a group of naturally occurring homologues. The redox-active quinoid moiety usually carries a polyprenoid side chain at position 6, the number of isoprenoid units in which is species-specific. Ubiquinones are involved in the control of mitochondrial electron transport, and are also potent anti-oxidants.
A sphing-4-enine in which the double bond is trans.
An optically active form of threonine having D-configuration.

A monohydroxypyridine that is pyridine substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3, an aminomethyl group at position 4, a hydroxymethyl group at position 5 and a methyl group at position 2. The 4-aminomethyl form of vitamin B6, it is used (in the form of the hydrochloride salt) for treatment of diabetic nephropathy.

Liposaccharide natural compounds consisting of a trisaccharide repeating unit (two heptose units and octulosonic acid) with oligosaccharide side chains and 3-hydroxytetradecanoic acid units (they are a major constituent of the cell walls of Gram-negative bacteria).
A 3-oxo Delta(4)-steroid that is androst-4-ene substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 17. It is a steroid hormone synthesized in the adrenal glands and gonads.
A member of the class of  phosphocholines that is the chloine ester of CDP. It is an intermediate obtained in the biosynthetic pathway of structural phospholipids in cell membranes.
An alpha-amino acid that consists of propionic acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2.
An L-alpha-amino acid that is the L-isomer of arginine.
The 17beta-isomer of estradiol.
The reduced form of NADP+; used in anabolic reactions, such as lipid and nucleic acid synthesis, which require NADPH as a reducing agent.
A nitrogen oxide which is a free radical, each molecule of which consists of one nitrogen and one oxygen atom.
Any neuraminic acid carrying an N-acyl substituent.
The R-enantiomer of serine.
A naturally occurring polypeptide synthesized at the ribosome.
A nucleotide sugar used as a donor by glycosyltransferases for the synthesis of sugar chains
A 2-aminooctadecane-1,3-diol having (2S,3R)-configuration.
A 20-oxo steroid that is pregn-5-ene substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3 and an oxo group at position 20.
A triamine that is the 1,5,10-triaza derivative of decane.
